April 30, 2026
1 A BILL TO BE ENTITLED
2 AN ACT TO ESTABLISH CAREER-READY LEAD TEACHER ACADEMIES TO PROVIDE
3 ALTERNATIVE PATHWAYS TO CAREERS IN CHILD CARE; TO APPROPRIATE
4 FUNDS TO THE NORTH CAROLINA PARTNERSHIP FOR CHILDREN, INC., TO
5 EXPAND MENTAL AND BEHAVIORAL HEALTH SERVICES FOR CHILDREN,
6 FAMILIES, AND STAFF IN CHILD CARE FACILITY SETTINGS AND ESTABLISH
7 THE NORTH CAROLINA PARTNERSHIP FOR CHILDREN, INC., SPECIAL FUND; TO
8 IMPLEMENT REFORMS REGARDING CHILD CARE CENTER ADMINISTRATORS
9 UNDER THE LAWS PERTAINING TO CHILD CARE; TO STUDY THE FEASIBILITY
10 OF PROVIDING LIABILITY INSURANCE COVERAGE FOR CHILD CARE
11 PROVIDERS; AND TO UPDATE THE BIDDING REQUIREMENTS FOR SMART
12 START.
13 The General Assembly of North Carolina enacts:
14
15 PART I. CAREER-READY LEAD TEACHER ACADEMY PILOT PROGRAM
16 SECTION 1.1. The purpose of this Part is to provide alternative pathways to career
17 advancement in licensed child care. To that end, the North Carolina Partnership for Children,
18 Inc., in collaboration with the North Carolina Community Colleges System Office, shall develop
19 and implement a two-year pilot program that expands the child care workforce academies
20 currently operating in Johnston and Wayne Counties. The pilot program shall establish
21 career-ready lead teacher academies across the State designed to provide free, comprehensive
22 training and support to individuals, with no experience or education in child care, who are
23 interested in pursuing a career in child care.
24 SECTION 1.2. Local partnerships in the following counties shall participate in the
25 pilot program described under this Part: Johnston and Wayne. The North Carolina Partnership
26 for Children, Inc. (NCPC), in collaboration with the Community Colleges System Office, shall
27 select 10 additional local partnerships to participate in the pilot program with at least one local
28 partnership selected from each of the four local partnership regions of the statewide Smart Start
29 network, which regions are the West, Mid-West, Mid-East, and East.
30 SECTION 1.3. The Community Colleges System Office and local community
31 colleges shall coordinate to ensure that graduates of the career-ready lead teacher academies meet
32 all requirements to be credentialed with the North Carolina Early Childhood Credential as lead
33 teachers in child care in this State.
34 SECTION 1.4.(a) Each child care career-ready lead teacher academy (academy)
35 shall seek to enroll no less than 10 students, with a goal of enrolling 15 students in each course.
36 The academy shall operate up to eight hours per day over a two- to three-week period. A
*H1086-v-2*

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 participating community college shall strive to offer an academy up to three times per year, with
2 at least one of the three academies occurring at the end of the traditional public school calendar
3 year to allow participation by interested high school and college students. The academy shall be
4 offered free-of-charge to applicants. Students participating in the academy shall receive the
5 knowledge, skills, and training, including the necessary health screenings, background checks,
6 and fingerprinting, required for employment as a lead teacher in a licensed child care program in
7 this State. Upon successful completion of the academy, each student shall receive either a North
8 Carolina Early Childhood Credential or a Provisional NC Early Childhood Credential that will
9 enable the student to begin working as either a lead teacher or group leader in a licensed child
10 care program immediately upon graduation.
11 SECTION 1.4.(b) A local partnership may provide each graduate with a one-time
12 stipend. If a one-time stipend for completing the course is provided, the amount shall be at the
13 discretion of the local partnership but shall not be less than one hundred fifty dollars ($150.00).
14 SECTION 1.4.(c) Students shall be eligible to receive an additional one-time stipend
15 in the amount of five hundred dollars ($500.00) in State funds after completing one year of
16 employment as a lead teacher in a licensed child care program in this State. To receive the
17 additional stipend under this subsection, the graduate shall do each of the following:
18 (1) Begin full-time employment as a lead teacher in a licensed child care center
19 or licensed family child care home within three months from the date of
20 graduation from an academy.
21 (2) Complete the one-year of employment required by this subsection within a
22 consecutive 12-month period at the same child care program.
23 SECTION 1.4.(d) The stipends provided under this section shall be available to a
24 graduate of an academy who is employed by a licensed child care facility in this State, including
25 a graduate who establishes a licensed family child care home.
26 SECTION 1.5. The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., and local
27 partnerships shall (i) collaborate with the community college in the county or counties in which
28 the local partnership is located, as practicable, to implement the career-ready lead teacher
29 academy and (ii) ensure information about the career-ready lead teacher academy in the
30 respective county is made available to the public.
31 SECTION 1.6. The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc. (NCPC), in
32 collaboration with the local partnerships and community colleges participating in the pilot
33 program, shall submit a progress report on the pilot program to the Joint Legislative Oversight
34 Committee on Health and Human Services and the Fiscal Research Division by March 31, 2027,
35 with any concerns or recommendations for program expansion. A final report shall be submitted
36 by December 31, 2027, and shall include, at a minimum, the following:
37 (1) The local partnerships and community colleges participating in the pilot
38 program.
39 (2) The number of students enrolled in each academy, by county.
40 (3) The number of students who successfully completed the academy, by county.
41 (4) The number of newly credentialed graduates employed as lead teachers in
42 licensed child care programs, by county.
43 (5) The outcomes achieved from the pilot program, including any
44 recommendations for expanding the program statewide.
45 (6) The number of new child care slots available as a result of adding the new
46 lead teachers.
47 (7) Total program costs, including any administrative costs borne by the county.
48 (8) The amount of funds needed to expand the program statewide.
49 SECTION 1.7. There is appropriated from the General Fund to the Department of
50 Health and Human Services, Division of Child Development and Early Education, the sum of
51 one million four hundred seventy-six thousand dollars ($1,476,000) in nonrecurring funds for the
Page 2 House Bill 1086-Second Edition

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 2026-2027 fiscal year to be allocated to the North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., to
2 provide the State match for implementing the pilot program described in this Part as follows:
3 (1) The sum of nine hundred seventy-two thousand dollars ($972,000) for the
4 2026-2027 fiscal year for the State portion of tuition costs.
5 (2) The sum of five hundred four thousand dollars ($504,000) for the 2026-2027
6 fiscal year for the stipends provided with State funds in accordance with
7 Section 1.4 of this Part.
8 SECTION 1.8. Funds described in Section 1.7 of this Part shall be used in
9 accordance with the following:
10 (1) The funds shall be allocated equally among the local partnerships selected to
11 participate in the pilot program.
12 (2) Local partnerships shall provide documentation of a twenty-five percent
13 (25%) local match as a condition of receiving State funds.
14 (3) Any unexpended and unencumbered funds at the end of the fiscal year from
15 the funds provided under this Part shall not revert to the General Fund but
16 shall remain available for use in accordance with this Part.
17 (4) The funds shall not be used for administrative costs.
18 (5) The funds are not subject to the administrative cost requirements under
19 Section 9D.5(b) of S.L. 2023-134, child care services funding requirements
20 under G.S. 143B-168.15(b), child care subsidy expansion requirements under
21 G.S. 143B-168.15(g), or match requirements under Section 9D.5(d) of S.L.
22 2023-134.
23 SECTION 1.9.(a) As a means to assist younger individuals with a career pathway
24 to provide child care services, the Department of Health and Human Services, Division of Child
25 Development and Early Education (DCDEE), shall establish a Provisional Early Childhood
26 Credential for individuals who are 16 or 17 years of age and preparing to work in licensed child
27 care programs in this State. To qualify for the provisional credential, an individual shall complete
28 an approved early childhood education course offered through a North Carolina public high
29 school (FE11), a Career and College Promise course (EDU 119), an Intro to School-Age Care
30 course (EDU 120 or EDU 2120), a Career and College Promise Workforce Continuing Education
31 pathway (EDU 3119), or Career-Ready Lead Teacher Academy.
32 SECTION 1.9.(b) By March 31, 2027, the North Carolina Community Colleges
33 System, the North Carolina Department of Public Instruction (DPI), the North Carolina Center
34 for Afterschool Programs (NC CAP), and DCDEE shall collaborate to ensure the required child
35 care health and safety trainings are embedded in each of the courses in subsection (a) of this
36 section so that individuals who are working to obtain the Provisional Early Childhood Credential
37 can access the required trainings through structured micro credentials, and, through this
38 collaboration, DCDEE shall ensure its trainings are available in the Moodle platform. The
39 Community Colleges System, DPI, NC CAP, and DCDEE shall also collaborate to create
40 pre-apprenticeship and apprenticeship pathways aligned with the Provisional Early Childhood
41 Credential. DCDEE shall issue the Provisional Early Childhood Credential to individuals who
42 meet the requirements established under subsection (a) of this section. The Provisional Early
43 Childhood Credential shall enable those individuals to work in any out-of-school and summer
44 programs, including those located at licensed child care facilities, as group leaders as defined in
45 the child care licensing rules according to the following staff-child ratios and group sizes:
46
47 Age Ratio Staff/Children
48 For a group that includes a child 5 years of age 1/10
49 For a group of children 6 years of age and older 1/14 to 1/16
50
