10 PART III. CHILD CARE REFORMS/CHILD CARE CENTER ADMINISTRATORS
11 SECTION 3.1. G.S. 110-91(8) is amended by adding the following sub-subdivisions
12 to read:
13 "a1. A licensed child care center may use the combined education and work
14 experience of two staff persons to meet the requirements for Level II
15 and Level III certificates or designation for the NC Early Childhood
16 Administration Credential certificate established by the Commission
17 and shall receive the same quality rating improvement system (QRIS)
18 credit toward a star-rated license as the center would receive if the
19 requirements were met by one staff person. To meet the requirements
20 of this sub-subdivision, the following requirements must be met:
21 1. One individual must complete EDU 261 and EDU 262 as set
22 out in the Child Care Rules in the Administrative Code, or the
23 equivalent, or hold an associate degree or higher in business
24 administration or a related field, or have at least two years of
25 verifiable business or administrative work experience.
26 2. One individual must (i) hold an associate degree or bachelor's
27 of science degree in early childhood education or child
28 development as designated by the Commission, (ii) be
29 responsible for the center's curriculum, program delivery, and
30 compliance practices, and (iii) be physically on-site for at least
31 the minimum number of hours required by the child care
32 staffing requirements set out under the Child Care Rules in the
33 Administrative Code.
34 a2. The Department shall allow an individual to earn the minimum
35 mandatory North Carolina Early Childhood Administration Credential
36 without completing coursework in EDU 261 and EDU 262, or the
37 equivalent of both, when the individual has (i) an associate degree or
38 higher in business administration or a related field or (ii) two years of
39 verifiable business or administrative work experience."
40 SECTION 3.2. This Part is effective when it becomes law.
41
42 PART IV. STUDY INSURANCE PROGRAM FOR CHILD CARE PROVIDERS
43 SECTION 4.1.(a) The Department of Insurance shall utilize a consulting firm, an
44 actuarial firm, a brokerage firm, or any combination thereof to study the feasibility of establishing
45 liability insurance coverage, including State-supported captive insurance, risk-pooling, joint
46 underwriting association, joint reinsurance, or other organizations, for North Carolina child care
47 providers in order to provide liability insurance coverage to participating child care providers,
48 which has the potential to support risk distribution while promoting strong governance and shared
49 accountability. All of the following shall be part of the study undertaken in accordance with this
50 subsection:
House Bill 1086-Second Edition Page 5

General Assembly Of North Carolina Session 2025
1 (1) The collection of loss data and operational information from child care
2 providers statewide in order to estimate program feasibility, premium
3 requirements, and necessary surplus levels.
4 (2) An evaluation of the viability of a program that is designed primarily to
5 provide general liability coverage, including a focus on sexual abuse and
6 molestation (SAM) coverage, whether offered separately or bundled.
7 (3) A determination of the amount of public funding needed to initially capitalize
8 the insurer and an exploration of potential alternative solutions to that public
9 funding.
10 (4) An analysis of conditions in the traditional, excess and surplus (E&S), and
11 unauthorized foreign reinsurance markets, including costs, affordability,
12 availability of liabilities coverages, and the barriers that child care providers
13 experience in accessing adequate liability coverage.
14 (5) A determination of whether commercial insurance carriers would be willing
15 to participate in this program, including discussion of developing an assigned
16 risk pool.
17 (6) The recommended design for the most viable program for North Carolina
18 child care providers.
19 (7) Identification of any legislative changes necessary to implement any
20 recommendations contained within the report, including any funding
21 recommendations.
22 SECTION 4.1.(b) The Department of Health and Human Services shall cooperate
23 with the Department of Insurance, and any entity with which the Department of Insurance has
24 contracted, for the purposes of supplying any information necessary to conduct the study required
25 by this section.
26 SECTION 4.1.(c) No later than June 1, 2027, the Department of Insurance shall
27 submit a report to the Joint Legislative Oversight Committee on General Government with the
28 findings of the study required by this section.
29 SECTION 4.1.(d) Effective July 1, 2026, there is appropriated from the General
30 Fund to the Department of Insurance the sum of three hundred fifty thousand dollars ($350,000)
31 in nonrecurring funds for the 2026-2027 fiscal year for the purposes of conducting the study
32 required by this section.
33
34 PART V. UPDATE BIDDING REQUIREMENTS FOR SMART START
35 SECTION 5.1. Section 9D.5(e) of S.L. 2023-134 reads as rewritten:
36 "SECTION 9D.5.(e) Bidding. – The North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc., and all
37 local partnerships shall use competitive bidding practices in contracting for goods and services
38 on contract amounts as follows:
39 (1) For amounts of five fifteen thousand dollars ($5,000) ($15,000) or less, the
40 procedures specified by a written policy as developed by the Board of
41 Directors of the North Carolina Partnership for Children, Inc.
42 (2) For amounts greater than five fifteen thousand dollars ($5,000) ($15,000) but
43 less than fifteen twenty-five thousand dollars ($15,000), ($25,000), three
44 written quotes.
45 (3) For amounts of fifteen twenty-five thousand dollars ($15,000) ($25,000) or
46 more but less than forty thousand dollars ($40,000), a request for proposal
47 process.process with solicitation in appropriate venues, including, but not
48 limited to, websites, major newspaper portals, or other options to ensure a
49 strong competitive process.
50 (4) For amounts of forty thousand dollars ($40,000) or more, a request for
51 proposal process and advertising in a major newspaper."
